# Engineering Standards

## KISS first

- Prefer the simplest solution that fully satisfies requirements.
- Avoid over-engineering, premature abstractions, and unnecessary configuration.
- Keep components, functions, and modules small and focused.

## TypeScript by default

- Write application code in TypeScript (`.ts` / `.tsx`) for type safety and maintainability.
- Avoid introducing plain JavaScript files unless required by tooling or third-party constraints.
- Add explicit types for public interfaces, component props, and shared utilities.

## Reusable component mindset

- When UI is likely reusable, extract it into a shared/global component instead of keeping it page-local.
- Keep shared components generic and configurable through typed props.
- Do not duplicate similar UI patterns across features when a shared component can cover them.

## Separation of concerns and folder conventions

- Keep constants in `const/` (or `constants/`) folders and utilities in `utils/` folders.
- Place shared types/interfaces in dedicated `types/` folders when reused across modules.
- Organize code by responsibility (UI, constants, utils, services, hooks, types) and avoid mixing concerns in one file.
